HILT: @Provides vs @Binds — COMPLETE COMPARISON
==============================================

@Provides
---------
WHAT IT DOES
• Tells Hilt HOW to create an object
• Acts like a factory method
• Hilt EXECUTES this method at runtime

OBJECT CREATION
• You manually create the object
• Example: return Calculator()

REQUIRES @Inject CONSTRUCTOR?
• ❌ NO
• The class can be a plain Kotlin/Java class

WHERE USED
• Inside a @Module class
• Can be object class or normal class

METHOD TYPE
• Normal function
• Has a method body

WHEN TO USE
• Third-party classes (Retrofit, OkHttp, Room)
• Classes you do NOT own
• Object creation needs logic
• No interface required

PERFORMANCE
• Slightly slower (method call)
• Negligible in real apps

EXAMPLE MENTAL MODEL
• "I will create this object for you"

----------------------------------------------

@Binds
------
WHAT IT DOES
• Tells Hilt WHICH implementation to use
• Acts like a mapping rule
• Method is NEVER executed

OBJECT CREATION
• Hilt creates the object itself
• Uses @Inject constructor of implementation

REQUIRES @Inject CONSTRUCTOR?
• ✅ YES (on the implementation class)
• Otherwise Hilt cannot create it

WHERE USED
• Inside a @Module class
• Module MUST be abstract

METHOD TYPE
• Abstract function
• No method body

WHEN TO USE
• Interface → Implementation binding
• You own the implementation class
• Simple, direct mapping
• No creation logic needed

PERFORMANCE
• Faster than @Provides
• Preferred by Hilt/Dagger

EXAMPLE MENTAL MODEL
• "When X is requested, use Y"

----------------------------------------------

SIDE-BY-SIDE SUMMARY
-------------------

@Provides
• HOW to create
• You build the object
• No @Inject constructor
• Can return any type
• More flexible
• More boilerplate

@Binds
• WHICH implementation
• Hilt builds the object
• Requires @Inject constructor
• Interface required
• Less boilerplate
• Faster

----------------------------------------------

GOLDEN RULE (VERY IMPORTANT)
----------------------------
• Object creation info must exist exactly ONCE

Creation can come from:
• @Provides  ✅
• @Inject constructor  ✅

----------------------------------------------

DECISION RULE (MEMORIZE THIS)
-----------------------------
• Prefer @Inject constructor
• Use @Binds for interface → implementation
• Use @Provides only when necessary
